[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1100},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F30\u002Fsimplest-way-to-deploy-gh-pages\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F30\u002Fsimplest-way-to-deploy-gh-pages\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F30\u002Fsimplest-way-to-deploy-gh-pages\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F30\u002Fsimplest-way-to-deploy-gh-pages\u002F":1076,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F30\u002Fsimplest-way-to-deploy-gh-pages\u002F":1085},"\u002Fgit\u002F20230530\u002F3386912069\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1058,"date":1059,"description":1060,"extension":1061,"lang":1062,"meta":1063,"navigation":1064,"path":1065,"readingMinutes":1066,"seo":1067,"standalone":1068,"stem":1069,"tags":1070,"tldr":1073,"updated":1059,"url":1074,"__hash__":1075},"content\u002Fen\u002FGit\u002Fsimplest-way-to-deploy-gh-pages.md","The Simplest Way to Deploy Your Own gh-pages Site","6209693386",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1048},"minimark",[11,19,24,27,31,34,37,53,64,74,96,99,133,136,139,143,146,149,152,163,171,176,187,406,412,457,461,467,472,478,578,588,595,601,605,608,611,642,649,655,667,674,915,928,933,936,951,958,963,966,971,980,987,1009,1016,1029,1033,1044],[12,13,14],"p",{},[15,16],"img",{"alt":17,"src":18},"gh-pages","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FGit\u002Fgh-paegs\u002FRay_GitHub_Pages_29a1b904-f2d3-4781-85f7-3c8db4acf558.png",[20,21,23],"h2",{"id":22},"intro","Intro",[12,25,26],{},"gh-pages is a free GitHub service that lets you deploy a static site for showcase purposes. For frontend devs that's super handy and useful. But there are a bunch of ways to deploy a gh-pages site, so this post walks through the simplest one.",[20,28,30],{"id":29},"what-is-gh-pages","What is gh-pages?",[12,32,33],{},"Quick intro first.",[12,35,36],{},"gh-pages stands for GitHub Pages. It's a free service from GitHub (the code-hosting platform) for deploying static sites. You can use it for your blog, portfolio, or quick demos.",[12,38,39,40,44,45,48,49,52],{},"It's also a special GitHub branch (if you know Git). If your repo has this branch, you can access your site at ",[41,42,43],"code",{},"https:\u002F\u002F\u003Cusername>.github.io\u002F\u003Crepository>"," — where ",[41,46,47],{},"\u003Cusername>"," is your GitHub handle and ",[41,50,51],{},"\u003Crepository>"," is your project name.",[12,54,55,56,59,60,63],{},"My handle is ",[41,57,58],{},"hsiangfeng",", so if my repo were ",[41,61,62],{},"israynotarray",", the URL would be:",[65,66,72],"pre",{"className":67,"code":69,"language":70,"meta":71},[68],"language-text","https:\u002F\u002Fhsiangfeng.github.io\u002Fisraynotarray\n","text","",[41,73,69],{"__ignoreMap":71},[75,76,77],"blockquote",{},[12,78,79,83,84,87,88,91,92,95],{},[80,81,82],"strong",{},"Note","\nOne more thing: you might've seen URLs like ",[41,85,86],{},"https:\u002F\u002F\u003Cusername>.github.io"," without the repo part. That's because the repo name matches the username. For me that would mean ",[41,89,90],{},"https:\u002F\u002Fhsiangfeng.github.io\u002Fhsiangfeng.github.io",", but since the repo name is the same as my username, the repo name gets dropped — leaving ",[41,93,94],{},"https:\u002F\u002Fhsiangfeng.github.io",".",[12,97,98],{},"And one more note — gh-pages is free as long as you have a GitHub account, but there are a few things to watch:",[100,101,102,106,109,112,115,118,121],"ul",{},[103,104,105],"li",{},"Static sites only. No backend — no PHP, Node.js, Python, etc. Just HTML, CSS, JavaScript. There's no server-side compute.",[103,107,108],{},"One gh-pages branch per repo. So if you need multiple sites, you need multiple repos.",[103,110,111],{},"Each repo's capacity is limited — 1GB. If your site goes over that, you can't deploy.",[103,113,114],{},"Bandwidth limit is 100GB per month.",[103,116,117],{},"gh-pages only allows 10 deploys per hour. If you roll your own GitHub Actions, that cap doesn't apply (because you're paying anyway).",[103,119,120],{},"Free SSL certs.",[103,122,123,124,126,127,132],{},"The default domain is ",[41,125,43],{},". For a custom domain, you'll need to buy one and configure DNS. See my earlier post ",[128,129,131],"a",{"href":130},"\u002Fen\u002Fmisc\u002F2022\u002F12\u002F06\u002Fbuy-a-domain-for-your-blog-with-github-pages-and-cloudflare\u002F","How to Buy a Domain and Connect Your Blog"," for details.",[12,134,135],{},"One more thing: gh-pages is free but not for commercial or illegal use — your account can get suspended. That's in GitHub's docs, so I won't dwell on it.",[12,137,138],{},"Now let's get to deploying gh-pages.",[20,140,142],{"id":141},"deploying-gh-pages","Deploying gh-pages",[12,144,145],{},"So I mentioned gh-pages is dead simple to use — all you need is a GitHub account. But how do you actually do it? Can you deploy a simple site even with minimal programming knowledge?",[12,147,148],{},"Yes, and it's really straightforward. You just need basic frontend and basic Git. Let's get into it.",[12,150,151],{},"A few setup steps I'll skip:",[100,153,154,157,160],{},[103,155,156],{},"Install VSCode (or any editor)",[103,158,159],{},"Create a GitHub account",[103,161,162],{},"Create a GitHub repo",[12,164,165,166,170],{},"You can handle these — and if you can't, no worries, my earlier post ",[128,167,169],{"href":168},"\u002Fen\u002Fhexo\u002F2020\u002F09\u002F24\u002Flearn-hexo-11-deploy-first-blog\u002F","(11) Learning Hexo: Deploy Your First Blog"," has detailed steps for creating a GitHub Pages repo.",[172,173,175],"h3",{"id":174},"set-up-the-basics","Set up the basics",[12,177,178,179,182,183,186],{},"Assuming you've got a GitHub account and a repo, head to your computer, create a folder called ",[41,180,181],{},"example",", and inside it create ",[41,184,185],{},"index.html",":",[65,188,192],{"className":189,"code":190,"language":191,"meta":71,"style":71},"language-html