:",[12,929,930],{},[15,931],{"alt":926,"src":932},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FGit\u002Fgh-paegs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202023-05-30%2010.13.50.png",[12,934,935],{},"Back in your terminal, run:",[65,937,939],{"className":480,"code":938,"language":482,"meta":71,"style":71},"npm run deploy\n",[41,940,941],{"__ignoreMap":71},[195,942,943,945,948],{"class":197,"line":198},[195,944,620],{"class":489},[195,946,947],{"class":230}," run",[195,949,950],{"class":230}," deploy\n",[12,952,953,954,957],{},"When you see ",[41,955,956],{},"Published"," in the terminal, you're deployed.",[12,959,960],{},[15,961],{"alt":956,"src":962},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FGit\u002Fgh-paegs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202023-05-30%2010.14.47.png",[12,964,965],{},"Head to your GitHub repo — you'll see a new gh-pages branch:",[12,967,968],{},[15,969],{"alt":17,"src":970},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FGit\u002Fgh-paegs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202023-05-30%2010.16.03.png",[12,972,973,974,976,977,95],{},"And the site is now live at ",[41,975,43],{}," — in this example, ",[41,978,979],{},"https:\u002F\u002Fhsiangfeng.github.io\u002Fexample-gh-pages",[75,981,982],{},[12,983,984,986],{},[80,985,82],{},"\nGitHub auto-detects the gh-pages branch — if it exists, it deploys. The deploy process shows up in the repo's Actions tab under \"pages build and deployment\". Once it turns green, you're deployed.",[12,988,989,990,992,993,996,997,999,1000,1003,1004,1006,1007,95],{},"Quick aside on how gh-pages works under the hood: in ",[41,991,672],{}," we added ",[41,994,995],{},"gh-pages -d src",". That tells gh-pages to push the contents of the ",[41,998,926],{}," folder to the gh-pages branch. The ",[41,1001,1002],{},"-d"," flag is short for directory — it specifies which folder to push. Without ",[41,1005,1002],{},", it defaults to the root, but you don't want to push everything (including node_modules) so we specify ",[41,1008,926],{},[12,1010,1011,1012,1015],{},"How does gh-pages know which repo to push to? It reads ",[41,1013,1014],{},".git","'s remote config — that's why we didn't have to specify a repo URL anywhere.",[75,1017,1018],{},[12,1019,1020,1022,1023,95],{},[80,1021,82],{},"\nIf you're using CRA or Vite, read the gh-pages docs — they have specific config requirements, otherwise the site might not work. Check the ",[128,1024,1028],{"href":1025,"rel":1026},"https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002Ftschaub\u002Fgh-pages#github-pages-project-sites",[1027],"nofollow","official docs",[20,1030,1032],{"id":1031},"bonus","Bonus",[12,1034,1035,1036,1039,1040,1043],{},"If you're using Vite (or similar build tools), change ",[41,1037,1038],{},"\"deploy\": \"gh-pages -d dist\""," to ",[41,1041,1042],{},"\"deploy\": \"vite build && gh-pages -d dist\""," so it builds before deploying.",[1045,1046,1047],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sKpQp, html code.shiki .sKpQp{--shiki-default:#72F088}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .s_sBn, html code.shiki .s_sBn{--shiki-default:#FFB757}html pre.shiki code .sQrFR, html code.shiki .sQrFR{--shiki-default:#BDC4CC}html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}",{"title":71,"searchDepth":216,"depth":216,"links":1049},[1050,1051,1052,1057],{"id":22,"depth":216,"text":23},{"id":29,"depth":216,"text":30},{"id":141,"depth":216,"text":142,"children":1053},[1054,1055,1056],{"id":174,"depth":236,"text":175},{"id":459,"depth":236,"text":460},{"id":603,"depth":236,"text":604},{"id":1031,"depth":216,"text":1032},"Git","2023-05-30 09:02:55","gh-pages is a free GitHub service that lets you deploy a static site for showcase purposes. For frontend devs that's super handy. But there are a bunch of ways to deploy, so this post walks through the simplest one.","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002Fsimplest-way-to-deploy-gh-pages","5",{"title":6,"description":1060},false,"en\u002FGit\u002Fsimplest-way-to-deploy-gh-pages",[1058,17,599,1071,1072],"GitHub Pages","Deployment",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F30\u002Fsimplest-way-to-deploy-gh-pages\u002F","mvd8cej9pjsaO9isSuwg9S1v8yrBimnZRiq1dGdmO3g",{"newer":1077,"older":1081},{"url":1078,"title":1079,"date":1080},"\u002Fen\u002Fmisc\u002F2023\u002F06\u002F03\u002Fwindows-cant-find-item-cannot-delete-file-fix\u002F","Windows \"Could Not Find This Item\" — When a File or Folder Refuses to Delete","2023-06-03 09:59:54",{"url":1082,"title":1083,"date":1084},"\u002Fen\u002Fmisc\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F27\u002Fautomate-google-forms-sheets-calendar-with-gas\u002F","Productivity Boost: Automate Google Forms, Sheets, and Calendar With GAS","2023-05-27 11:17:05",[1086,1091,1096],{"url":1087,"title":1088,"date":1089,"readingMinutes":1090},"\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2026\u002F02\u002F26\u002Fgit-push-force-with-lease-better-than-force\u002F","A Safer Alternative to git push --force: git push --force-with-lease","2026-02-26 09:39:40","4",{"url":1092,"title":1093,"date":1094,"readingMinutes":1095},"\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2026\u002F01\u002F22\u002Fgit-default-branch-master-to-main\u002F","Git init Shows a master Branch Hint? Here's How to Set main as Default","2026-01-22 16:20:40","3",{"url":1097,"title":1098,"date":1099,"readingMinutes":1066},"\u002Fen\u002Fgit\u002F2026\u002F01\u002F21\u002Fgit